		<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comment clearfix li-comment highlander-comment" id="comment-615643" data-comment-id="615643">
			<div class="div-comment" id="div-comment-615643">
				<div class="comment-meta clearfix">
					<div class="comment-author-avatar">
						<a class="avatar-placeholder" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2a551d3a1501b508b4e15f3e1ec53e6b?d=retro&amp;s=55&amp;r=pg"></a>					</div>
					<div class="comment-info">
						<cite>Wes</cite>
						<a href="http://gigaom.com/2011/04/08/10-things-you-never-knew-you-could-do-on-your-ipad/#comment-615643" class="comment-permalink">Saturday, April 9 2011</a>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="comment-content">
					<div class="comment-text">
						<p>Since I don&#8217;t have a Mac, I was bummed out that I couldn&#8217;t enable the multi-touch gestures.  After doing a little research, there&#8217;s a way to do it from a PC.  You have to install a free (nagware) program called iBackupBot, do a backup, and then edit a registry key in the backup, and then restore it to your iPad.  The gestures will be enabled, but the option won&#8217;t show up in the menu.  There&#8217;s a good tutorial located at <a href="http://www.icopybot.com/blog/enable-multitouch-gestures-on-ipad-without-jailbreaking.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.icopybot.com/blog/enable-multitouch-gestures-on-ipad-without-jailbreaking.htm</a>.  I followed this and it worked like a charm.</p>
					</div>
